<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF109-562-895  </DOCNO><DOCID>09 562 895.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>IBM System User  Sept 1990 p17(4).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Windows of choice. (graphical user interface)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Jackson, Peter.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>The user interface is what determines whether computerapplications are useful or a hindrance.andP;  A graphical userinterface (GUI) specifies how the human-machine interface shouldwork, giving users the ability to make educated guesses about howa new program works.andP;  There are a variety of GUIs available, andthe GUI selected can determine software and hardware requirements.andO;How the GUI is mapped onto the operating system varies.andP;  The GUIand the operating system on the Apple Macintosh are essentiallythe same.andP;  The GUI is built on top of the existing MS-DOSoperating system in Microsoft Windows and is a shield around theoperating system so users do not see the MS-DOS command prompt.andO;IBM's OS/2 Presentation Manager is also built on top of theoperating system, but it is just a shell program for OS/2.andP;  IBMand Microsoft are using hardware requirements to separate Windowsand Presentation Manager.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Product:   Apple Macintosh (Microcomputer) (Usage)OS/2 Presentation Manager (Graphical user interface) (Usage)Microsoft Windows (Graphical user interface) (Usage).andO;Topic:     Graphical User InterfaceMicrocomputersOperating SystemsUser Interface.andO;Feature:   illustrationphotograph.andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>